enhancing concept-based pragmatics instruction -- tPart IV: Current issues in L2 pragmatics -- t13 Explicit knowledge in L2 pragmatics? -- t14 Studying speech acts: An expanded scope and refined methodologies -- t15 Converging agendas of rationalist and discursive approaches for the development of a pedagogy of L2 pragmatics -- t16 From a native-nonnative speaker dichotomy to a translingual framework -- t17 An introduction to discourse markers -- tEpilogue: A personal tribute to Andrew Cohen -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNew Directions in Second Language Pragmatics brings together varying perspectives in second language (L2) pragmatics to show both historical developments in the field, while also looking towards the future, including theoretical, empirical, and implementation perspectives. This volume is divided in four sections: teaching and learning speech acts, assessing pragmatic competence, analyzing discourses in digital contexts, and current issues in L2 pragmatics. The chapters focus on various aspects related to the learning, teaching, and assessing of L2 pragmatics and cover a range of learning environments. The authors address current topics in L2 pragmatics such as: speech acts from a discursive perspective; pragmatics instruction in the foreign language classroom and during study abroad; assessment of pragmatic competence; research methods used to collect pragmatics data; pragmatics in computer-mediated contexts; the role of implicit and explicit knowledge; discourse markers as a resource for interaction; and the framework of translingual practice. Taken together, the chapters in this volume foreground innovations and new directions in the field of L2 pragmatics while, at the same time, ground their work in the existing literature. Consequently, this volume both highlights where the field of L2 pragmatics has been and offers cutting-edge insights into where it is going in the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 4aPragmatik. 4aZweitspracherwerb. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aSecond Language Pragmatics, Pragmatics Instruction, Assessment, Digital Discourses.1 aBardovi-Harlig, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoxer, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiBartolomeo, Megan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEde-Hernandez, Luz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllis, Rod, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernández, Loretta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFraser, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFélix-Brasdefer, J. César, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFélix-Brasdefer, J. César, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGómez, Tania, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIshihara, Noriko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJiang, Yuechun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnight, Stephanie W.P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMir, Montserrat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlshtain, Elite, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRodríguez, Enrique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoever, Carsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoss, Steven J., econtributor.4ctb4https:/